PHR: Project Narrative We seek to validate, calibrate, and translate restricted spectrum imaging (RSI-MRI) across vendors to asses in the detection of clinically significant prostate cancer. RSI-MRI is a novel sequence protocol with software post- processing accomplished along with standard of care MRI to improve the quality of prostate MRI imaging. The research has the potential to revolutionize prostate cancer diagnosis and monitoring by providing a non-invasive imaging biomarker with the ability to improve diagnostic accuracy and risk stratification across MRI scanners.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Gastric cancer is a leading cause of mortality in Latinos. This proposal will characterize the epigenome of common and aggressive genomically stable (GS) gastric tumors in Latinos, model their tumorigenesis using ethnic-appropriate Latino gastric organoids, and identify GS tumor vulnerabilities using a loss of function screen. Our study will generate a body of data that will be useful in understanding GS tumor biology and in addressing cancer disparities in this population.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
PHR: Project Narrative The objective of this Katz R01 project is to develop a novel multi-scale computational model to: 1) quantify the local and systemic hemodynamics (i.e., pressure, flow rate, shear stress, oxygen transport, etc.) during phases of active hemorrhage, aortic occlusion with REBOA, and resuscitation, 2) identify vascular regions that are vulnerable to ischemic damage as a result of the altered hemodynamics, 3) predict key physiologic responses related to vascular compliance, oxygen delivery and renal autoregulation during hemorrhage and aortic occlusion, and 4) determine optimal aortic occlusion size and duration of partial vs. full REBOA strategies to prevent ischemia-reperfusion injuries and renal failure. At its core, this proposal builds on the PIâ€™s training in cardiovascular fluid mechanics, trauma and shock, but represents an important new direction that has the potential to transform the field of hemorrhagic shock research.

PHR: Individual hosts vary in their susceptibility to pathogens, which has important consequences for outbreak dynamics and pathogen evolution. Our work will elucidate relationships between prior exposure of hosts to pathogens, as occurs naturally and via vaccination, and the degree of variability in host susceptibility. The models generated will be broadly useful for understanding and managing any pathogens, including those of humans, where host protection generated by prior exposure is variable, incomplete, or wanes over time.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Blood malignancies are characterized by recurrent somatic mutations in RNA splicing factors that drive aberrant splicing to promote leukemogenesis. Recently, a novel species of RNA called circular RNAs (circRNA) was discovered to be aberrantly expressed in many types of liquid cancers, yet the role of RNA splicing factors mutations on the biogenesis of these molecules, if any, in promoting leukemogenesis is not known. Establishing a link between known RNA splicing factor mutations and circRNAs could define a novel regulatory axis that can be exploited for targeted therapy of these diseases.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF DIABETES AND DIGESTIVE AND KIDNEY DISEASES
PHR: This research will investigate how a protein hormone (parathyroid hormone, PTH) is able to interact with the surface of a cell in bone and transmit signals to the cell's DNA to regulate the expression of genes involved in bone breakdown. PTH is essential for maintaining serum calcium levels, but too much of the hormone or genetic diseases that act like PTH can cause major bone loss and disabilities. The results of our research will help develop treatments for hyperparathyroidism and other bone and skeletal disorders in place of surgery.

PHR: The most recent conflicts are creating a new generation of veterans, including an increasing number of women veterans, who present with comorbid PTSD and chronic pain conditions, including Fibromyalgia (FM), from deployment-related physical injuries and exposure to psychological trauma. Health behavior change is important in treating these conditions and proactively preventing long-term negative health sequelae, in order to benefit these veterans directly and reduce the challenges to our healthcare system. The proposed SPiRE application will use an innovative translational research approach to study whether a progressive -based exercise program will reduce FM pain in patients with PTSD and to elucidate and modify potential PTSD- related deficiencies in neurobiological and psychological responses to exercise to optimize the physical and psychological benefits of exercise for these individuals.

IC_NAME: EUNICE KENNEDY SHRIVER NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF CHILD HEALTH & HUMAN DEVELOPMENT
PHR: While mothers' adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) can undermine their capacity to provide sensitive care that is essential for healthy child development, positive childhood experiences (PCEs) may be a source of resilience that buffers the deleterious effects of ACEs on parenting and their children's health. The proposed K99/R00 study aims to elucidate the relationships among mothers' ACEs and PCEs, maternal sensitivity, and immune regulation in infants and toddlers of mothers living with opioid-dependence, a high-risk group often exposed to a host of adversities. The expected findings may help explain the heterogeneity in outcomes in populations exposed to substantial adversity and will illuminate potential biobehavioral pathways of intergenerational transmission of adversity and resilience.

PHR: NARRATIVE The proposed research examines neurodevelopmental mechanisms underlying the powerful association of stressful life events (SLEs) with internalizing and externalizing psychopathology during adolescence. We use a novel methodological approach that permits examination of dynamic changes in emotion, cognition, social behavior, and neural function and connectivity following SLEs at a sufficiently fine grained level of temporal specificity to identify mechanisms underlying the link between SLEs and adolescent psychopathology as they unfold in real time. Elucidating these mechanisms will not only build knowledge of how environmental experience shapes development in ways that increase risk for psychopathology, but will also suggest possible targets for interventions to prevent the onset of stress-related psychopathology in children and adolescents.

PHR: NARRATIVE Human skin, like all other tissues, undergoes an intrinsic aging process during an individualâ€™s lifespan known as chronological aging, as well as photoaging, since the skin is constantly exposed to environmental factors such as UV radiation (UVR), which is recognized as the major risk factor for the development of many skin cancers. In the skin, there is an age-associated accumulation of senescent melanocytes, keratinocytes and fibroblasts capable of expressing the senescence-associated secretory phenotype (SASP), which promotes inflammation and have a profound deleterious effect on skin structure and integrity. We will generate 3D skin models that encompass critical biological variables for mapping senescent cells in tissues, and will include: 1) both genders; 2) the full range of skin pigmentation phototypes; and 3) age ranges across the human lifespan, to investigate the mechanisms leading to senescence in the skin and test new approaches to treat age-related conditions.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Single cell multi-omics profiling assays (e.g., single-cell RNA-seq, ATAC-seq, proteomics) have opened new windows into understanding the properties, regulation, dynamics, and function of senescence at unprecedented resolution and scale, however, these assays are inherently destructive, precluding us from tracking the molecular profiles and dynamics of live cells in tissues, whole organisms, or humans. We aim to develop an innovative technology â€œSenNetRamanâ€ by combining the recent advance in high-resolution and -speed Raman microscopy, single-cell and spatial multi-omics, and machine learning to unbiasedly map the molecular and cellular heterogeneity and spatial information of senescent cells nondestructively. Overall, we believe â€œSenNetRamanâ€ is highly modular and lays a foundation for future investigations into exploring single-cell genome-wide molecular dynamics of senescent cells in tissues through imaging data, in vitro and in vivo in humans.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE New technologies and experimental pipelines are needed to accurately phenotype and quantify senescent cells within their distinct microenvironments. We propose to develop iterative and integrated spatially-resolved imaging mass cytometry and digital-spatial transcriptomics for determination of senescent cell identity and abundance across mouse and human tissues, beginning with analyses in the aged mouse brain. This novel, scalable molecular mapping technology can ultimately be used to facilitate assessment of and extent to which senescent cells contribute to age-related tissue dysfunction, with broad relevance to human therapy development.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE In this application, I propose a set of genetic, biochemical and bioinformatics studies to understand: 1) the role of ADAR1 RNA editing in regulation of the maternal transcriptome in the oocyte and early embryo in young and old mice, and 2) the effect of ADAR1 RNA editing on RNA stability in oocytes and eggs from young and old mice. These mechanistic studies will advance our basic understanding of how post-transcriptional RNA processing is integral to the oocyte RNA environment, and hence, oocyte quality. The knowledge gained from this proposal could promote a shift in current paradigms and redirect research to accelerate progress in understanding infertility and disease.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE The ultimate goal of this research is to evaluate the feasibility, acceptability and preliminary impact of incorporating choice in the delivery of ART support to patients who return to HIV care after an interruption, a growing population who are vulnerable to future interruptions. The development of patient-centered interventions is a key priority area to bridge remaining HIV treatment gaps in high-burden settings like South Africa. If proven to be acceptable, feasible and effective, incorporating choice in the delivery of ART support in routine, high-burden HIV care settings may be an important tool to promote patient empowerment and improve ART adherence and retention.

ORG_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE ON DEAFNESS AND OTHER COMMUNICATION DISORDERS
PHR: Extensive research has been done on the measurement and causes of smell and taste disorders.  These disorders can be screened with a series of simple questions with inexpensive, brief odor identification tests and taste intensity tests coupled with further questions (problems past year, since age 25, phantom and altered sensations) that can screen for marked dysfunction. NIH-funded centers and research investigators provide direction for treatment of these disorders.  When properly diagnosed, some causes of impaired taste and smell are treatable. Treatments include: 1) over-the-counter or prescription medications, 2) quitting smoking if a smoker, 3) dental care, 4) changing medications or doses if current medications are causing impaired taste and smell, 5) chronic sinusitis, treated with antibiotics, and 6) surgery to remove nasal polyps. The causes of olfactory dysfunction that are most amenable to treatment include obstructing polyps or other masses (treated by excision) and inflammation (treated with steroids).  Nutritional counseling with enhancement of food flavor and appearance and maintenance of healthful eating and weight can improve quality of life in patients with irreversible dysfunction.  Health care providers should be prepared to offer education (particularly to older adults) about avoiding hazardous events if they have impaired senses of smell and taste.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF NEUROLOGICAL DISORDERS AND STROKE
PHR: Astrocytes, the most abundant glial cells in the central nervous system, perform a multitude of evolutionary conserved functions including, metabolic support to neurons, regulating blood-brain barrier, and modulating synapse-formation, -function and -plasticity, and are crucial in maintaining normal brain homeostasis. Dynamic crosstalk between astrocytes and neuronal synapses modulates most if not all of these functions, yet the molecular mechanism of neuron-astrocyte cross-communication at the synapse is largely untapped. Based on our preliminary studies, we propose a novel mechanism of neuron-astrocyte crosstalk at the synapse via S1P/S1PR1 signaling that regulates astrocyte function and neuronal synapse formation, function and plasticity.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF NEUROLOGICAL DISORDERS AND STROKE
PHR: Project Narrative Despite much effort to identify mechanisms underlying amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and frontotemporal lobar degeneration dementia (FTLD or FTD), effective treatments remain elusive. Motoneuron (MN) excitability dysfunction is tightly linked to disease pathology, yet to date, excitability dysregulation has not been examined in the recent rNLS8 mouse model, which recapitulates pathologic TDP43 inclusions seen in MNs in >90% of ALS patients and in FTD patients. This proposal is relevant to public health because it will examine excitability dysregulation in this highly relevant model of ALS/FTD.

PHR: Project Narrative Kinases are an important class of proteins that are currently targeted by 77 small molecule FDA-approved drugs, more than 85% of which can be used in cancer therapy. Despite them performing essential roles in the brain, modulating kinases to treat neurodegeneration has not been the focus of most programs, leaving their potential to alter or halt the progression of these diseases unknown. This project will create high-quality chemical tools that can be used in animals and will allow researchers around the world to more definitively characterize the suggested role that one of these important kinases plays in driving Alzheimerâ€™s disease pathology and confirm whether it is a good therapeutic target for Alzheimerâ€™s disease.

PHR: Narrative: The class-IIa histone deacetylases (class-IIa HDACs) are a key component of the epigenetic machinery in Alzheimer's disease (AD), a devastating neurodegenerative disease. Therefore, developing and validating a novel class-IIa HDAC PET imaging probe will have a significant positive impact on human health by informing on AD progression and may detect AD at an early time point when therapy may be most effective. The success of our imaging studies may delineate a novel role for class-IIa HDAC in pathophysiology and progression of AD and may identify class-IIa HDAC as a novel druggable target in AD.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE â€“ Overall. People with Down syndrome are strongly predisposed to develop a wide range of comorbidities that shorten their lifespan and decrease their quality of life, such as Alzheimerâ€™s disease, congenital heart disease, leukemias, autoimmune disorders, and diverse neurological conditions. The proposed activities under this project seek to create a world-class resource for collaborative discovery, data sharing, data access, and integrative analysis that would enable novel investigations into all DS comorbidities across the lifespan and further integrating across datasets for related diseases occurring in the general population, thus paving the way for a precision medicine approach to DS. Furthermore, this resource and associated platforms will also have broader impacts by empowering physicians, educators, government officials, and advocates with the tools required to elicit evidence- based transformative action in the clinic, the classroom, the government, and society at large.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE The androgen receptor is a type I nuclear hormone receptor and master transcription factor responsible for differentiation and development of the male phenotype. Its hyperactivation is associated with multiple diseases, including metastatic prostate cancer, androgenetic alopecia, androgen insensitivity syndrome, and Kennedyâ€™s disease. This proposal seeks to understand the mechanism of androgen receptor regulation and determinants of its aberrant activity using biochemical, structural, and cellular methods, which can facilitate the development of novel androgen receptor inhibitors and lend mechanistic insight towards other related nuclear hormone receptors.

IC_NAME: EUNICE KENNEDY SHRIVER NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF CHILD HEALTH & HUMAN DEVELOPMENT
PHR: NARRATIVE Spontaneous preterm birth is a leading cause of neonatal morbidity and mortality, yet we lack the means to diagnose it in advance, treat, or prevent it, especially in women giving birth for the first time. We will analyze samples from one of the best-phenotyped cohorts of nulliparous pregnant women, the nuMoM2b study, providing the largest sample size of its kind along with detailed clinical data affording a nuanced view of prematurity. Our study will identify new biomarkers for early identification of preterm birth, and potential mechanisms underlying it, through a high-resolution investigation of the microbes and small molecules in the female reproductive tract.

PHR: We propose to evaluate the safety, tolerability, and efficacy of a pre- and peri-hematopoietic stem cell transplant (HCT) prebiotic intervention to improve the health of the gut microbiota (bacteria in the gut) and HCT outcomes. Our phase 1/randomized phase 2 clinical trial is accompanied by stool-based correlative studies to understand the impact of our prebiotic intervention on the microbiota and differences in the microbiota that may explain why some patients respond to the prebiotic while others may not; we also include peripheral blood biomarkers to identify potential mechanisms to explain the interaction between the prebiotic, microbiota, and HCT outcomes.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF GENERAL MEDICAL SCIENCES
PHR: Project Narratives Building on our success in using novel cryoEM methods to obtain the first near-atomic resolution structures of viral genomes, the largest human viral particles, and small (~120 kDa) membrane protein complexes, this continuation project aims to make atomic resolution structure determination a routine practice for large and transiently stable biological complexes, particularly endogenous cellular complexes and in situ structures in viral genome packaging and gene transcription processes. These new methods will enable investigators to place individual components (proteins, nucleic acids and lipids) within the context of the larger assembly and to visualize chemical interactions among the parts of the complex at atomic detail. Broadly, structural studies of various macromolecular complexes enabled by these new methods will lead to atomic models, help to understand their mechanisms of action, inform efforts to rationally design drugs and vaccines, and suggest novel targets for therapeutic intervention.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Self-care is an evidence-based strategy that can reduce the high morbidity and mortality associated with heart failure. However, little is known about how to implement self-care for heart failure in low- and middle-income country settings in ways that account for the unique needs of different cultures and contexts. Our study, which is designed to prioritize health equity throughout all phases, will compare the implementation, effectiveness, and cost effectiveness of a digital-first implementation strategy vs. a basic evidence-based package and current standard of care to improve self-care in heart failure.

PHR: Narrative Schizophrenia is a highly heritable neurodevelopmental disorder, but the mechanisms behind how schizophrenia genetic risk loci function is not clear. Cortical interneurons are substantially affected in schizophrenia and enriched for schizophrenia heritability during development. The proposed study is aimed at identifying schizophrenia risk loci that are active in these neurons during development, which will provide insights on the developmental mechanisms of SCZ risks, and help identify novel therapeutic targets.

PHR: Neurodegenerative diseases, including Alzheimerâ€™s disease (AD) and Alzheimerâ€™s disease related dementias (ADRD) are characterized by accumulation of intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs) and impairment of proteasome-mediated protein degradation. This R36 proposal aims to investigate small molecule 20S proteasome activation as a novel strategy to resolve both pathogenic events. Successful completion of this work will enable the rapid design, development, and identification of 20S proteasome activators, and elucidate the role of 20S proteasome modulation in neurodegenerative diseases as a novel therapeutic strategy for disease treatment.

PHR: Narrative Human iPSCs can provide unlimited sources of human neurons to study disease mechanisms; but in vitro neuronal cultures lack many important brain components that play crucial roles in neuronal functions. Thus, we will generate brain-region-specific humanized cortical interneuron mice to allow for the study of the role of grafted human neurons in brain circuit and behavioral functions. Such physiological humanized models will facilitate the understanding of cell-type-specific and brain-region-specific disease mechanisms, and the development of novel therapeutics.

PHR: The studies proposed herein are designed to investigate mechanisms of immune evasion following active immunotherapy with brain cancer vaccines. We will test our hypothesis that clinically relevant anti-tumor immunity to glioblastoma (GBM) must have two cellular components: 1) significant infiltration of tumor-specific  tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (TIL); and 2) blockade of immunosuppressive tumor infiltrating myeloid cell (TIM) function within the tumor microenvironment. We believe that a combination of active vaccination (ATL-DC; to induce T-cell infiltration into tumors), immune checkpoint inhibition (to enhance T cell function), and CSF-1R inhibition (to block suppressive TIM function) may lead to improved outcomes for the treatment of glioblastoma.

PHR: Project narrative Production of small molecules that bind metal ions is important for the survival of microbes and the ability of these microbes to cause infections. We study the reaction mechanisms of the enzymes responsible for the production of a unique copper-containing antibiotic, which is produced by a pathogen that can cause serious hospital-acquired infections. Our mechanistic investigations will advance the understanding of enzyme-catalyzed reactions, provide new tools for biocatalysis, and enable studies of how pathogenic bacteria maintain copper balance during infection.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Acute myeloid leukemia (AML) remains an incurable malignancy despite the recent approval of molecularly targeted therapies. The Bcl-2 antagonist/BH3 mimetic, venetoclax, is routinely used in combination with chemotherapy or hypomethylating agents in newly diagnosed AML, but incomplete responses demonstrate a need for novel treatment modalities to improve venetoclax efficacy. The F99 phase of this proposal investigates the mechanisms of synergy and in vivo efficacy of co-inhibiting the pro-survival sphingolipid enzyme, acid ceramidase, and Bcl-2 in AML, while the K00 phase leverages CRISPR screening and dynamic BH3 profiling to develop rational sphingolipid-based drug combinations in breast cancer.

PHR: Narrative Noncoding structural variants (SVs) represent a largely undefined component of the genetic architecture of developmental disorders (DDs). There are a handful of examples of noncoding SVs associated with long-range positional effects (LRPEs) that result in DDs, but the characterization of LRPEs and the delineation of their underlying mechanism has not been systematically investigated. The proposed studies will investigate the prevalence and molecular mechanisms contributing to pathogenic LRPEs in DDs by performing SV association analysis with large case control cohorts as well as paired transcriptomic and chromatin profiling in individuals with large chromosomal abnormalities to identify features predictive of LRPEs across the genome.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Fragile X syndrome (FXS), the most common inherited form of intellectual disability and a leading genetic cause of autism spectrum disorders (ASD), is caused by the loss of functional fragile X mental retardation protein (FMRP). Recent technological development of 2D and 3D culture derived from human iPSCs provides a new platform to investigate human brain development in a dish, otherwise inaccessible to experimentation. This multi-project Center aims to establish a framework to understand the FMRP-mediated regulation of human brain development at molecular, cellular and system circuitry levels that will enable the development of therapeutic approaches to treat FXS.

PHR: Project Narrative The area postrema, a brain circumventricular sensory organ regulated by both humoral signals and inputs from the gastrointestinal tract, plays a critical role in nausea and aversive behaviors. During my postdoctoral fellowship, I identified and characterized a population of area postrema neurons which mediates aversive behaviors, and here I will specify and map both humoral and vagal inputs to these area postrema neurons and understand their physiological effects. Acquiring expertise required to achieve these aims, namely hormone signaling and functional circuit mapping, will enable me to establish an independent research program which focuses on the cellular and neural mechanisms of nausea combining mice and vomiting animals, and may lead to the development of novel anti-emetic therapies.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE We aim to adapt and pilot a guided self-help stress management program from the World Health Organization and to incorporate peer cancer survivors in providing psychosocial support to breast cancer patients in Viet Nam. We seek to demonstrate the feasibility of the culturally and contextually adapted intervention in reducing the psychological distress associated with cancer diagnosis and treatment, to ultimately improve cancer patientsâ€™ health outcomes. Successful completion of the project begins to fill the gaps in the lack of culturally appropriate evidence-based mental health interventions for cancer patients in many low- and middle-income countries, and in many racial/ethnic groups in the U.S.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Harmful menstrual practices, such as chhaupadi (menstrual seclusion) in Nepal, are an urgent threat to womenâ€™s health, wellbeing, and development. This study will investigate underlying mechanisms of promising aspects of chhaupadi interventions to date and build upon these findings to co-design and pilot test a context- specific intervention in partnership with community members. In the short-term, outcomes from this proposal will advance the field by resulting in 1) a pilot tested intervention that can be further tested in a future randomized controlled trial, 2) a refined approach for engaging communities in sustainable and contextually appropriate intervention co-design that is expected to be applicable to other low- and middle-income country contexts, and 3) in the longer-term support public health efforts aiming to reduce the negative health effects of harmful menstrual practices on women in Nepal.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Moderate to vigorous intensity physical activity is known to reduce the risk of hypertensive disorders of pregnancy and other adverse pregnancy outcomes that increase future maternal cardiovascular disease risk, yet less than 25% of pregnant women meet public health activity guidelines. More than 95% of the 24-hour day is spent in sedentary behavior, sleep, or light-intensity activity; however, the impacts of these lower intensity activities on adverse pregnancy outcomes are unknown. This multi-site observational cohort study will leverage state-of-the-art, 24-hour behavior assessment in each trimester of pregnancy and examine associations with adverse pregnancy outcomes to inform guidelines and future interventions designed to improve womenâ€™s pregnancy and long-term cardiovascular health.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
PHR: NARRATIVE Poor cardiovascular health (CVH) contributes greatly to maternal morbidity and mortality in the United States, and many families enrolled in home visiting are at risk for poor CVH. Improving CVH requires focusing on CVH risk factors, 2-generation strategies addressing mothers and children, and greater use of settings where families already receive care. The Johns Hopkins Early Intervention to Promote Cardiovascular Health of Mothers and Children (ENRICH) Resource and Coordinating Center will generate rigorous, innovative, timely and actionable new knowledge to promote CVH and reduce CVH disparities in mothers and young children.

PHR: Project Narrative  The proposed research will create a novel diagnostic tool for managing sickle cell disease based on a new high throughput cellular screening technology for evaluating red blood cells. There is currently no objective measure of vaso-occlusive crisis in sickle cell disease but the proposed technology will allow researchers and doctors to examine every single cell in a sample in a short amount of time using holographic images and machine learning. This technology can be used at the point of care to provide better information on the health of red blood cells for sickle cell disease patients.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Vascular remodeling is process where vascular smooth muscle cells (SMC) transition from a differentiated phenotype to a proliferative state and plays a critical role in the development of diseases such as asthma, atherosclerosis, systemic hypertension and cancer. Here, we propose a combination of molecular, cellular and genetic approaches utilizing gain-of-function or loss-of-function studies to establish a novel mechanism regulating SMC phenotype modulation. Completion of this proposal will increase our understanding of mechanisms that contribute to the progression of proliferative vascular diseases and will result in the identification of a novel protein target to develop therapies to treat such diseases.

PHR: Project Narrative  Our proposal will be focused on increasing capacity in the Middle East and North Africa in environmental health research and especially with regards to climate change. There is a major gap in research capacity in this field despite the region is already suffering the health consequences of climate change in terms of increased frequency of heatwaves, desert dust storms, and drought and low frequency of precipitation. The hub will create the platform to expand and sustain this focus as the state-of-art go to entity in the region to help the populations and decisions makers address the climate change health impacts.

ORG_NAME: UNIVERSITY OF OKLAHOMA HLTH SCIENCES CTR
PHR: Project Narrative Dual-smoker couples (i.e., both members of a couple) are prevalent and treatment-resistant; they also confront unique challenges that may reduce the impact of standard treatments. The proposed randomized controlled trial systematically examines the efficacy, mechanisms, and cost effectiveness of implementing financial incentive treatments in this population. Support for the efficacy of dyadic financial incentive treatments for dual-smoker couples would be a scalable population-level intervention for a refractory subgroup of smokers.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL CENTER FOR COMPLEMENTARY & INTEGRATIVE HEALTH
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE  People with schizophrenia are characterized by marked impairments in cognitive function, for which there are no current pharmacological treatments. The development of an effective intervention for cognitive impairments remains a major therapeutic challenge. Prebiotics are dietary fibers that promote the growth or activity of gut microorganisms, which leads to the enhanced well-being of the host. The proposed R61 and R33 projects are designed to evaluate the hypothesis that prebiotic administration will lead to increased production of butyrate, through increased activity of butyrate-producing bacteria in the gut microbiota; the increase in serum butyrate levels will be associated with changes in cognitive function, symptoms, and metabolic measures.

ORG_NAME: UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN AT ANN ARBOR
PHR: We have developed and clinically translated the combination of trabectedin and irinotecan as an EWS-FLI1 targeted therapy for Ewing sarcoma. While the clinical evaluation of this combination is promising and multiple tumor regressions have been observed, the activity has been limited by what appears to be intrinsic mechanisms of resistance. The goal of the current study is to exploit these mechanisms to develop novel EWS-FLI1 directed combination therapies with improved activity and less toxicity.

ORG_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE ON DEAFNESS AND OTHER COMMUNICATION DISORDERS
PHR: Hearing is important. Good hearing ability is an essential aspect of normal communication and plays an important role in safety and awareness in nearly every part of daily life.  Hearing trouble results in a myriad of difficulties, including communication trouble, difficulty at school or work, social isolation and/or stigmatization, potentially accelerated cognitive decline, and economic ramifications at the family, community, and national level.  Adults with hearing impairment are at risk for decreased quality of life, poorer health status, and diminished health care services received. Targeted interventions delivered in a community or medical setting, provided by audiologists, Ear, Nose, and Throat (ENT) doctors [aka, Otolaryngologists-Head and Neck surgeons], neuro-otologists, occupational and physical therapists, pediatricians, gerontologists, and other trained health care workers can potentially mitigate risks for long-term disability.   Hearing loss is a widespread problem. It is the third most common chronic physical condition in the United States and is twice as prevalent as diabetes or cancer.  Recent statistics indicate that 37.5 million U.S. adults aged 18 and older have some degree of hearing impairment.  Approximately 50 million Americans report tinnitus (ringing in the ears), a condition that can be as disabling as hearing loss.  Over 16 million of these individuals suffer frequent tinnitus, and about 2 million experience tinnitus so severe that it interferes with daily living activities.  Nationally, the total cost of first-year hearing loss treatment is projected to multiply five-fold between 2002 and 2030, from $8.2 billion to $51.4 billion. These NHANES epidemiological audiometric data will also provide national reference distributions â€“ normative data â€“ that can be used to screen for deficiencies across the U.S. population, and with the oversampling of minorities and other economically-disadvantaged individuals, it provides a barometer for disparities.   Most adult-onset hearing losses are permanent.  In the U.S., noise exposure is a major cause of preventable hearing loss.  Twenty-two million U.S. workers are exposed to noise annually, and 24% of hearing difficulty among workers is attributable to workplace noise exposure.  Noise-induced hearing loss (NIHL) is the second most commonly reported occupational disease and the most expensive disability for military and Federal workersâ€™ compensation.  In recent years, some factors may have resulted in reduced loud noise exposure, such as better industry compliance with OSHA noise standards, implementation of noise-reducing innovations in the workplace, as well as the continuing shift of jobs away from manufacturing sector in the U.S. economy.  Noise does not just occur on-the-job; approximately 21 million adults have acquired a non-occupational NIHL.  Sources for non-occupational noise exposure include firearms use and many environmental or recreational exposures to loud music or noise, such as frequent attendance at loud sporting events and working with electrical tools or machinery.  As the Nationâ€™s population ages and survival rates for infants and for people with severe injuries and acquired diseases improve, the prevalence of hearing loss and other communication disorders is expected to rise.

PHR: Project Narrative Mutated KRAS is a highly prevalent oncoprotein driving a number of cancers, but pharmacological inhibition is  limited to only the G12C mutant despite over thirty years of research. Here, we propose to develop an  antisense oligonucleotide-based therapeutic agent which takes advantage of our proprietary delivery  technology. Building upon strong efficacy indication in non-small cell carcinoma mouse models, we will perform  additional structure optimizations, conduct toxicology/pharmacology studies in both mice and non-human  primates, and obtain additional indications in advanced preclinical animal models.

PHR: Project Narrative  In the present project we propose to address critical gaps in our understanding of the risk posed by Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) circulation in dairy cattle and its shedding in milk from affected animals. Our team will investigate the efficacy of raw milk cheese aging- and will determine the kinetics of virus inactivation in several dairy products. Additionally, we will identify products that can inactivate the virus in raw milk, so that these products can be used to mitigate the risks posed by raw milk to other animals and to humans. .

PHR: Project Narrative Cardiovascular and kidney disease frequently co-exist for reasons that are poorly understood. Soluble urokinase plasminogen active receptor (suPAR) is a recently discovered cause of kidney disease and a strong marker of cardiovascular risk, and we propose studying the role for suPAR in cardiovascular disease and testing the hypothesis that people with high suPAR levels have early and progressive atherosclerosis, independently of its known impact on the kidneys. Understanding the role of suPAR as a novel pathogenic factor of CVD and biomarker of risk will lead to the design and study of therapeutic and preventive interventions with wide reaching impact.

PHR: Project Narrative We seek to understand why some children with single ventricle heart disease fail after surgical procedures. Currently, images from echocardiography, catheterizations, and cardiovascular magnetic resonance are being used to qualitatively choose the best surgical approach for these patients. In this project, we aim to quantitatively determine the most optimal surgical repair for each patient by simulating different surgical repairs and comparing the post-surgical hemodynamics.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Stochastic fluctuations in gene expression impact cell-fate specification decisions from embryogenesis to viral infection creating barriers for effective treatment interventions. Based on therapeutic precedents in neuroscience that use fluctuations to improve sensorimotor function, this project will identify centralized molecular and cellular mechanisms of noise modulation, that can be therapeutically targeted, in embryonic stem cells (ESCs). The proposed research will lead to development of new broad-spectrum noise modulators, and propel clinical translation of noise-modulating molecules to guide new therapeutic approaches that overcome barriers to precise cell-fate control in diverse mammalian systems.

PHR: Project Narrative: Acquired resistance to therapy contributes to poor survival outcomes in cancer patients. The primary objective of this U54 application is to establish a successful and self-sustaining ARTNet Center for Pancreatic Cancer (ACPC) to explore novel mechanisms and combination therapies to target acquired resistance in pancreatic cancer. We will collaborate and work closely with other ARTNet centers, coordinating center, and the National Cancer Institute to provide novel mechanistic insights and translational opportunities to target therapy resistance with the long-term goal of improving overall patient survival.

PHR: The world is in need of an effective HIV/AIDS vaccine, and the cytomegalovirus (CMV) vector-based HIV/SIV vaccine featured in our studies is highly efficacious and durable to uniquely mediate viral â€œreplication arrestâ€ efficacy in the Rhesus Macaque-SIV model. Vaccine immunity is mediated by unconventional MHC-E-restricted CD8+ T cell responses and induction of IL-15, which correlate with vaccine protection. The work proposed in this application will reveal the molecular mechanisms of immune programming by the CMV-based vaccine and IL- 15 actions to inform human testing of this vaccine concept in ongoing and future phase I/II trials.

PHR: Communication problems or disorders of voice, speech, and language (VSL) are primary mission areas of the National Institute on Deafness and Other Communication Disorders (NIDCD), NIH.  Disorders involving VSL can have an overwhelming effect on an individualâ€™s health and quality of life. These disorders affect people of all ages with or without hearing impairment, including children with autism, those who stutter, and adults with aphasia or speech disorders. The functions, skills, and abilities of voice, speech, and language are related.  It is important to recognize functional health impairments, including delayed childhood development, and seek early evaluation by health care professionals, e.g., early interventionists and speech-language pathologists (SLP), to identify the problem(s) and select effective treatment(s). The information obtained will become a Public Use dataset approximately six-months following the end of data collection and, hence, available for analysis and dissemination by research investigators and for other purposes, including providing updates to track progress in achieving national objectives formulated for this decadeâ€™s Sensory and Communication Disorders topic area of Healthy People 2030.

PHR: Project Narrative The goal of the Center for Innovative NeuroTech Advancement (CINTA) is to rapidly transform emerging technologies into commercially viable, clinically focused solutions for disorders of the nervous system as a hub under the NIH Blueprint MedTech: Incubator Hubs program. CINTA will support the advancement of neurotechnology solutions by adapting and improving upon the proven model that CIMIT developed and implemented for RADx Tech to accelerate promising neurotechnologies that address critical areas of unmet needs in the diagnosis and treatment of nervous system disorders to human-grade prototypes. CINTA plans to find, fund, facilitate, and accelerate 15 projects per year through this program.

We propose to (i), develop a cadre of trained Ghanaian scientists who can use data science approaches to tackle prominent child health problems, (ii) build faculty and institutional capacity for data science at KNUST, and (iii) develop competencies to ensure Ghanaian biomedical data science teams work effectively and synergistically. Trainees will develop skills and acquire experience with real world data science problems that address 3 of the top 10 ten causes of child death and disability in Ghana: malaria, injury and congenital malformations.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF NEUROLOGICAL DISORDERS AND STROKE
PHR: Project Narrative We have recently developed a new non-invasive brain stimulation (NIBS) system, kilohertz transcranial magnetic perturbation (kTMP) that opens up a new experimental space for safely modulating neural excitability in targeted areas of the human brain. This project will characterize the broad parameter space of kTMP in terms of tolerability and efficacy in healthy individuals. The results from this work will set the stage for full-fledged clinical trials in patients with neurological disorders such as stroke or spinal cord injury, two areas in which NIBS methods show promise as tools to facilitate neurorehabilitation.

ORG_NAME: STATE UNIVERSITY NEW YORK STONY BROOK
PHR: Urine cadmium and risk of fracture and bone loss Narrative Mechanistic experiments and cross-sectional epidemiologic studies have linked cadmium to low bone mineral density, osteoporosis, and fracture; however, currently lacking are large prospective epidemiologic studies. We propose to leverage existing samples and data from the two largest prospective US osteoporosis cohort studies to perform an in-depth investigation of cadmium, bone loss, and fractures. These studies promise to transform the field of Cd-bone research and have high potential to impact policy decisions in the US and globally.

PHR: Project Narrative GA NCORP Community Site addresses two important challenges in US public health: expanding cancer research to a broader population and including underserved populations in cancer research. Advances in clinical care and scientific discovery are not currently equally available to all races and ethnic groups. GA NCORP will continue to analyze data to identify areas for potential improvement, identify proven best practices, and utilize the expertise of research network affiliates and disparities experts to develop and enhance efforts to achieve equitable access to clinical trials.

PHR: Project Narrative The UCSF Discovering cancer Risks from Environmental exposures And Maternal/child health (DREAM) cohort is designed to fill current gaps in knowledge about the role of environmental exposures in cancer etiology by engaging with a diverse population of pregnant women. Through focusing on this critical, but understudied window of exposure, our study will contribute to an enhanced understanding of the relationships between multiple exposures to environmental contaminants and intermediate cancer risk biomarkers. In the long term, results can support earlier identification of risk factors, allowing for more effective prevention of environmentally mediated cancers.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE This research infrastructure project will harmonize and merge multiple data sets needed to answer new and complex questions about the aging trajectories and health of diverse populations during the universal process of aging. This project is relevant to the National Institute on Ag- ingâ€™s mission to support clinical, social, and economic research on aging.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF BIOMEDICAL IMAGING AND BIOENGINEERING
PHR: Rapid, inexpensive detection of protein biomarkers of disease at the point of care is critical for many clinical purposes but is currently not possible for many important clinical targets. Here, we propose a new detection technique that uses in vitro, protein-based signaling networks incorporating self-amplifying enzymatic pathways that results in biomarker detection platforms with unparalleled sensing capabilities in less than two minutes. While initial detection designs will be applied for the point-of-care detection of Hepatitis C Virus, the detection system can be applied to sense any protein or small molecule biomarker with known binders, and as such could be used as a platform for the detection of many analytes currently unable to be rapidly detected at the point of care.

IC_NAME: EUNICE KENNEDY SHRIVER NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF CHILD HEALTH & HUMAN DEVELOPMENT
PHR: NARRATIVE On June 24, 2022, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled to eliminate federal protections for abortion access through the Dobbs v. Jackson Womenâ€™s Health decision. Our study will evaluate the evolving, time-sensitive impact of the Dobbs decision on people with childbearing capacity, particularly those with chronic diseases. This project will examine: 1) experiences of people seeking abortion, to understand the immediate and long-term consequences of abortion receipt or denial on health and well-being; 2) experiences of physicians who provide care for people with chronic diseases, to describe ways in which evolving abortion policy affects medical decision-making and practice; and 3) population-level data, to generate new evidence about the impact of abortion policy on clinical outcomes, including severe maternal morbidity and maternal mortality.

IC_NAME: EUNICE KENNEDY SHRIVER NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF CHILD HEALTH & HUMAN DEVELOPMENT
PHR: The landscape of reproductive health care in the United States is in the midst of seismic and rapid shifts; abrupt changes in access to abortion in the US are without precedent in terms of the number of individuals who are affected, the number of states in which there remains substantial uncertainty around abortion policy changes in the near future, and the scale of potential effects on the lives of pregnant people. This project addresses the urgent need to assess the impact of state abortion restrictions on the health of pregnant people, as well as the need for high quality estimates of abortion incidence both within and outside of the formal health care system as these restrictions are implemented. This study will advance the field of abortion measurement by establishing estimation approaches that encompass both facility-based and self-managed procedures and are designed for a context in which the legal status of abortion is hybridized and subject to rapid, ongoing changes, laying the foundation for a new surveillance infrastructure that will be needed for the foreseeable future.

ORG_NAME: UNIVERSITY OF SOUTH CAROLINA AT COLUMBIA
PHR: Metabolic dysregulation, an important manifestation of inflammation, may hold the key for addressing the growing problem of Early-Onset CRC (EOCRC) (i.e., <50 years), and numerous other obesity-related cancers. The proposed work draws on experience that we have accumulated in working with inflammation, and metabolic dysregulation in particular, in both laboratory animal experiments and human studies and that have contributed many hundreds of papers and thousands of citations to the medical literature over the last 10 years. Results from this work, which meld our wide-ranging experience in transdisciplinary science, have important implications for advancing the science and real, practical implications for addressing cancer-related disparities that have consistently disfavor African Americans, a group that is uniquely metabolically obese (i.e., evince symptoms associated with obesity at lower levels of overall adiposity).

IC_NAME: OFFICE OF THE DIRECTOR, NATIONAL INSTITUTES OF HEALTH
PHR: Environmental exposures profoundly shape lifespan health and disease trajectories. The ECHO Measurement Core will advise, orchestrate, and frame the coordinated, sensitive measurement of exposures, developmental processes, and health outcomes central to achieving ECHO's objective of mapping the impact of early exposures on child health and development. We will develop and refine measures for the ECHO Cohort Protocol (ECP), including methods to implement the measures that are culturally sensitive and valid for diverse populations, assist the ECHO Consortium in implementing and evaluating the ECP, and we will lead strategic decision-making and operational strategies to incorporate new and revised measures to advance ECHO Cohort science while minimizing participant and staff burden.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
ORG_NAME: UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN AT ANN ARBOR
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE High dietary sodium intake is linked to incident hypertension (HTN) and cardiovascular events. Conversely, lower sodium intake has been shown to reduce both blood pressure (BP) and prevent atherosclerotic cardiovascular diseases (ASCVD). American Heart Association guidelines advocate daily sodium intake of less than 2,300 mg, but the estimated average sodium intake for Americans is 3,400 mg per day. In recent years, consumption of pre-processed and restaurant foods has substantially increased, and more than 75% of sodium in the average U.S. diet now comes from these sources. Our overall objectives are to: (1) evaluate the efficacy of a dietary sodium mobile application intervention on reducing BP, (2) establish that the improvement in BP is directly related to the change in diet and body weight, and (3) optimize the intervention to demonstrate sustained effects on BP.

PHR: Correlating structural changes in the region of the brain caused by cognitive impairment with those in shape and molecular in the same region will be important for understanding cognition in aging. In turn, this may help to understand pathological changes associated with cognitive impairment. Such analysis is challenging and can be analyzed by powerful tools that consistently preserve information across scales from the macroscopic one of magnetic resonance scans to the microscopic scales of histologic images and molecular changes.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF ALLERGY AND INFECTIOUS DISEASES
PHR: Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Corona Virus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), the causative agent of the Covid-19 pandemic, infects the host cell by binding its spike protein with the angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2) on the host receptor cells. Structurally, spike protein has two subunits, S1 and S2, and is a trimer, while the ACE2 protein is a homodimer; however, critical questions about the dynamics of the molecular interactions to activate the membrane fusion remain. This project will determine the dynamics of each molecular interaction associated with the SARS-CoV-2 entry, thus helping to design more effective countermeasures.
PROJECT_TERMS: NA
PROJECT_TITLE: Understand the mechanism of SARS-CoV-2 entry by single-molecule approaches

IC_NAME: EUNICE KENNEDY SHRIVER NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF CHILD HEALTH & HUMAN DEVELOPMENT
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Poor postpartum health has implications for maternal mortality and infant outcomes. However, eligibility for pregnancy-related Medicaid ends after 60 days postpartum, leading to high rates of postpartum insurance loss. The proposed project evaluates how the Medicaid continuous coverage requirement during the public health emergency affected postpartum coverage, care, and infant care overall, by maternal race-ethnicity, and during various periods of the COVID-19 pandemic context, with implications for state postpartum Medicaid extensions under the American Rescue Plan.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL HEART, LUNG, AND BLOOD INSTITUTE
ORG_NAME: WEILL MEDICAL COLL OF CORNELL UNIV
PHR: Project Narrative Patients with Hypersensitivity Pneumonitis experience poor health-related quality of life without access to interventions that target improvement in this outcome. The goal of this proposal is to develop and determine the feasibility and acceptability of a stakeholder-engaged behavioral and educational intervention to improve the health-related quality of life of patients with hypersensitivity pneumonitis. Findings from this innovative pilot randomized trial will lay the groundwork for a future, multi-site, randomized trial testing the effectiveness of the intervention developed here.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF DENTAL & CRANIOFACIAL RESEARCH
PHR: Project Narrative Craniofacial defects are among the most common of all congenital abnormalities. An embryonic population of cells called the neural crest gives rise to a significant portion of the craniofacial complex, including bone and cartilage of the face, pigment cells, and components of the peripheral nervous system. My work seeks to understand how a subfamily of transcription factors (SoxE) help the neural crest form the diversity of cell types in the face and how patient specific SOXE mutations cause Campomelic dysplasia and Waardenburg syndrome.

PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE The goal of this study is to generate supportive scientific evidence for strategies that will facilitate informed decision-making about PS&D by diverse populations of pregnant patients as early as possible in their prenatal care. By achieving the aims of this study, this study will meet the critical need to provide resources to patients as they consider a changing array of PS&D and post-diagnosis options that have significant implications for their health, their pregnancy, and their family. This study is significant for patient care as it will be a critical step toward establishing patient-centric strategies and resources that can effectively support evidence-based reproductive healthcare in an increasingly complex healthcare setting.

PHR: NARRATIVE: PROJECT 1: TARGETING GLIOMA TISSUE STATES Glioblastoma (GBM) biopsies are composed of not only molecularly aberrant malignant glioma cells but also a  sizeable abundance of non-malignant cells (including immune, astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, etc.). The goal of  this project is to find targetable cross-talk relationships between these cell compositional networks. Specifically,  we will quantify different cellular compositions in pre- and post- treatment tumors, investigate cross-talk between  the glioma cells and the microenvironmental other cell subpopulations, and, lastly, determine the impact of  targeting this crosstalk to shift the cell community composition into a more favorable/treatable state.

PHR: NARRATIVE: PROJECT 2: IMAGING THE DYNAMIC TISSUE STATE IN PATIENTS IN VIVO Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) measures many different physical properties of the tissue which may be  correlated with the specific tumor behavior (e.g., proliferation, inflammation, angiogenesis) found in the limited  biopsies available per patient. This project will fuse readily available MRI to spatially localized biopsies to build  predictive models of cellular composition across the unsampled tumor (and brain) to track and validate cell composition changes to standard and immune therapies. Connecting these imaging changes to patient survival  will allow identification of clinically beneficial shifts in cellular cohabitation.

PHR: NARRATIVE: OUTREACH CORE Getting computational results into the clinic requires a broader understanding of the methods and general  principles by scientists, clinicians, and patients alike. To accomplish our goal, we  will train new cross-disciplinary scientists, inform the research community, engage with the general public, and  assess our outcomes.

PHR: Narrative: Biomaterial-enhanced delivery of chemoimmunotherapies represents a promising strategy to safely target multiple immune resistance pathways and induce direct cytotoxic and immune-mediated tumor control. Here, we will identify and quantify changes in the MHC Class I peptide repertoire with cell-type resolution in a genetically engineered GBM mouse model upon treatment with chemoimmunotherapy regimens and correlate these changes with therapy immunomodulatory mechanisms and survival. MHC peptides upregulated after treatment will be used to develop targeted immunotherapies (e.g., genetically engineered T cells, peptide vaccines) that will significantly enhance the efficacy of chemoimmunotherapy.

PHR: Project Narrative  Adenomas are early lesions of colorectal cancer (CRC), but only a subset of individuals develop adenomas, and only a subset of adenomas progress to cancer. We hypothesize that adenoma development and progression require adenoma autonomous factors (e.g. cancer driver gene mutations) in concert with adenoma nonautonomous factors pertaining to the gut microbial microenvironment. Our proposed studies will examine the direct causal relationships and interactions of adenomas, the colonic microenvironment, and the gut microbiome as â€œco-conspiratorsâ€ of adenoma initiation and/or progression.

PHR: Project Narrative  The Alaska Native community faces a high burden of colorectal cancer (CRC), with the highest incidence and mortality rates in the US. This study aims to investigate the link between the gut microbiome and colorectal adenomas, the early precancerous lesions in CRC, specific to this population. Through microbiome profiling of  unique collections of fecal samples, we will identify gut microbial biomarkers for colorectal adenomas.

PHR: Project Narrative Synthetic biology holds the promise of transforming the development of diagnostic and treatment strategies for various diseases. This project applies synthetic biology approaches to reprogram fate decisions toward progressive cellular deterioration, a key factor in many diseases, such as cancers, diabetes, and neurodegenerative diseases. Key insights obtained from this project will define foundations for chemical or gene- based strategies to treating diseases related to progressive cellular deterioration.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF ALLERGY AND INFECTIOUS DISEASES
PHR: T-cells are a type of white blood cell that are needed to fight infections and can be artificially programmed to destroy cancer cells in patients. The goal of this project is to define whether increasing the activity of the gene BCL11B will expedite recovery of T-cells after bone marrow transplantation and improve the ability of programmed T-cells to kill cancer cells. The potential benefit of the knowledge gained from this project is the development of new methods to improve the recovery of the immune system after bone marrow transplantation, and ways to more effectively program T-cells to fight cancer.
